05:26.059 --> 05:38.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The European
Commission
ruled today that Ireland must
collect $14.5

05:38.939 --> 05:41.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
billion in back taxes from
Apple.

05:41.608 --> 05:46.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The announcement fueled new
tensions between
the U.S. and Europe over the
role of multinational

05:46.046 --> 05:50.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
corporations, how they are
taxed, and whether
it should be considered a
subsidy.

05:50.717 --> 05:55.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The antitrust regulator for the
E.U. said
Ireland had given Apple a
sweetheart tax deal

05:55.622 --> 06:00.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for well over a decade, with
special laws
that effectively allowed Apple
to pay less

06:00.827 --> 06:03.296 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
than 1 percent corporate tax.

06:03.330 --> 06:08.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The E.U. accused Apple of
setting up two companies
in Ireland with a head office
that only exists

06:08.835 --> 06:10.570 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on paper.

06:10.604 --> 06:14.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The profits from European stores
all go to
the Ireland head office and are
essentially

06:15.008 --> 06:16.476 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
untaxed.

06:16.509 --> 06:20.080 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Apple said it would appeal the
decision and
denied the characterization.

06:20.113 --> 06:23.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a statement, the company's
chief executive,
Tim Cook, said the European
commission is

06:23.283 --> 06:29.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trying to -- quote -- "rewrite
Apple's history
in Europe, ignore Ireland's tax
laws and upend

06:29.122 --> 06:31.825 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the international tax system in
the process."

06:31.858 --> 06:35.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The company has more than $200
billion in
cash.

06:35.328 --> 06:39.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I spoke with Commissioner
Margrethe Vestager,
who announced the decision.

06:39.065 --> 06:41.234 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mr. Vestager, thanks for joining
us.

06:41.268 --> 06:47.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First off, what gave Apple an
edge in Ireland
that was unfair in the eyes of
the E.U.?

06:47.507 --> 06:52.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER, European
Commission: Well,
we have a long longstanding
prohibition of

06:52.512 --> 06:58.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
state aid, which means benefits,
advantages
to a selected company.

06:58.385 --> 07:04.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that may come in any form,
as a piece
of land, a favorable loan, a
grant or a tax

07:04.457 --> 07:05.792 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
benefit.

07:05.825 --> 07:09.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, of course, any member state
can have
their own tax legislation.

07:09.562 --> 07:11.398 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We would never question that.

07:11.431 --> 07:16.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the thing is that you cannot
give a specific
company a benefit or an
advantage which is

07:17.003 --> 07:18.838 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
not open to other companies.

07:18.872 --> 07:22.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is there
evidence that this
was specific to Apple and not to
all the other

07:22.809 --> 07:25.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
companies that are doing
business in Ireland?

07:25.145 --> 07:27.947 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER: Yes, it is.

07:27.981 --> 07:36.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This arrangement is due to two
things which
are none of our concern, how
Apple is organized

07:36.256 --> 07:38.558 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and the Irish tax legislation.

07:38.591 --> 07:45.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the thing that is specific
is two tax
rulings -- are two tax rulings
that are directed

07:45.365 --> 07:47.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
specifically to Apple.

07:47.233 --> 07:53.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And tax rulings are, by nature,
specific because
they are directed from the
government or from

07:53.673 --> 07:57.110 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the authorities to a specific
company.

07:57.143 --> 07:58.912 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And this is only for them.

07:58.945 --> 08:00.613 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It is not for other companies.

08:00.647 --> 08:05.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of Apple's
concerns
today, in a call with reporters,
the CFO said

08:05.785 --> 08:10.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the .005 percent effective tax
rate that you
cited this morning during your
press conference,

08:10.523 --> 08:12.192 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they said that -- "I said it
before.

08:12.225 --> 08:13.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a completely made-up
number.

08:13.560 --> 08:16.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We paid $400 million of taxes in
Ireland during
2014.

08:16.696 --> 08:19.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We're one of the largest
taxpayers in the
country."

08:19.699 --> 08:25.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER: Well, the
thing is that
it is important for profits to
be paid where

08:25.772 --> 08:27.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
profits are made.

08:27.941 --> 08:37.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we have seen is that
the Irish tax
rulings allowed Apple to put the
huge majority

08:37.217 --> 08:42.389 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of their profits into a
so-called headquarter
or head office.

08:42.422 --> 08:45.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This head office only existed on
paper.

08:45.091 --> 08:52.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It had no employees, no
premises, no real
activities, and it wasn't taxed,
not in Ireland,

08:52.999 --> 08:54.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
nor anywhere else.

08:54.734 --> 09:00.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that, of course, then led to
the result
that Apple paid very, very, very
little in

09:00.473 --> 09:06.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
taxes compared to their profits,
in some years,
as little as 0.005 percent.

09:06.846 --> 09:13.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is this part
of a broader
effort to redefine how
multinational corporations

09:14.020 --> 09:15.622 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pay taxes?

09:15.655 --> 09:18.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have heard that you're also
going after
McDonald's and reportedly
Amazon?

09:18.191 --> 09:23.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER: Well, the
thing is that
I do state aid control, and
state aid control

09:23.797 --> 09:26.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do not redefine taxation as
such.

09:26.099 --> 09:30.236 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That, of course, takes the
legislature to
work.

09:30.270 --> 09:36.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is why we have worked
with the European
Council, with the European
Parliament in order

09:36.042 --> 09:45.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to change legislation, to make
transparency
greater, to have
country-by-country reporting,

09:45.418 --> 09:49.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for tax authorities actually to
know what
other tax authorities are doing.

09:49.989 --> 09:53.693 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it is for the legislature to
change that.

09:53.726 --> 09:59.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I do is what we have a
longstanding tradition
of doing and a longstanding
court practice

09:59.432 --> 10:06.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of doing, which is to control
state aid seen
as specific advantages to
specific companies.

10:06.105 --> 10:11.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Doesn't this
draw into conflict
the role of the European Union
or the Commission

10:11.411 --> 10:16.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
vs. countries and their
sovereignty and how
they're able to lay out their
tax laws?

10:16.115 --> 10:21.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER: Well, the
sovereignty
of the member state is protected
by our treaty.

10:21.788 --> 10:24.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I, of course, respect that
100 percent.

10:24.624 --> 10:26.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have sworn to respect the
treaty.

10:26.893 --> 10:32.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the thing is that two things
have to be
in place at the same time, both
upholding

10:32.065 --> 10:38.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
national legislation as tax
legislation and,
at the same time, the European
legislation

10:38.204 --> 10:42.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we have made in common,
that -- the E.U.
state aid rules.

10:42.075 --> 10:48.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here we have a situation
where you have
Irish states -- Irish tax
legislation, but

10:48.281 --> 10:54.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a breach of European state aid
rules, because
illegal state aid was handed
out.

10:54.587 --> 10:56.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For the
record, we did invite
Apple.

10:56.289 --> 10:58.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They didn't have anybody
available today.

10:58.091 --> 11:02.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they did say in a statement
that this
could have a profound and
harmful effect on

11:02.595 --> 11:04.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
investment and job creation in
Europe.

11:04.664 --> 11:06.499 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They employ about 6,000 people
in Ireland.

11:06.533 --> 11:08.334 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Do you expect that?

11:08.368 --> 11:12.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER: Well, the
thing is that
Europe is a wonderful place to
do business.

11:12.205 --> 11:17.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a single market with more
than 500 million
potential customers.

11:17.377 --> 11:20.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a place where you find
research and development
of highest quality.

11:20.914 --> 11:26.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You find very skilled people,
good people
to employ, wonderful
infrastructure.

11:26.185 --> 11:30.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So you're more than welcome to
come to Europe
to do business.

11:30.390 --> 11:32.959 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think you can have a very
good business
here.

11:32.992 --> 11:37.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The thing is that what we don't
like so much
is if you come to Europe for tax
avoidance.

11:37.163 --> 11:42.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is there a
concern that
this is -- the uncertainty
between how the

11:43.002 --> 11:48.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
E.U. rules on different laws
inside member
nations could create a climate
where a company

11:48.775 --> 11:51.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
might not come to Europe; they
might base
themselves somewhere else?

11:51.778 --> 11:58.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER: I think
there is an issue
here also of corporate culture,
because, if

11:58.351 --> 12:03.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're in a country where the
tax rate is
12.5 percent, as in Ireland, and
you pay less

12:03.756 --> 12:09.662 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
than 1 percent, also
substantially less than
1 percent, well, then I think
you should also

12:09.696 --> 12:12.999 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
reconsider if everything is all
right.

12:13.032 --> 12:18.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And 12.5 percent is, in the
first place, a
very low corporate taxation
compared to other

12:18.104 --> 12:19.539 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
European member states.

12:19.572 --> 12:21.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Margrethe
Vestager, thanks
so much for joining us.

12:21.941 --> 12:23.109 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGRETHE VESTAGER: It was a
pleasure.

12:23.142 --> 12:28.214 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you for having me.

12:28.247 --> 12:41.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Cataloging the
atrocities committed
by the so-called Islamic State
group in Syria

12:41.127 --> 12:44.697 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
and Iraq is a difficult,
sometimes impossible
task.

12:44.731 --> 12:50.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A new report from the Associated
Press attempts
to document the mass graves
holding some of

12:50.069 --> 12:51.471 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the group's victims.

12:51.504 --> 12:56.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The AP found 72 mass grave sites
around Syria
and Iraq.

12:56.275 --> 13:00.179 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One of the sites held as many as
1,700 bodies.

13:00.213 --> 13:04.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more, we are joined by
Associated Press
reporter Lori Hinnant, one of
the authors

13:04.317 --> 13:05.451 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the investigation.

13:05.485 --> 13:07.920 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Lori, thank you for joining us.

13:07.954 --> 13:12.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Seventy-two mass grave sites,
how were you
and your colleagues able to find
them and

13:12.859 --> 13:14.260 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
document them?

13:14.293 --> 13:16.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LORI HINNANT, Associated Press:
Well, we used
a variety of sources.

13:16.262 --> 13:23.736 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We first went to Iraqi
Kurdistan, where there
are at least 35 mass graves on
Sinjar Mountain

13:23.770 --> 13:27.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
alone, most of them holding the
bodies of
minority Yazidi.

13:27.874 --> 13:35.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We also talked to the Kurdish
regional government,
who told us of at least two
others, one outside

13:35.381 --> 13:42.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mosul at a prison, where 600 to
800 inmates
were killed, and another in a
deep natural

13:42.355 --> 13:44.357 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
geological pit.

13:44.390 --> 13:48.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then we asked the government in
Baghdad what
they knew to try and triangulate
some of the

13:48.327 --> 13:49.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
other information.

13:49.829 --> 13:54.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We also went into archives of
news reports
when sites were discovered.

13:54.701 --> 13:56.469 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
For Syria, we can't go in.

13:56.502 --> 14:02.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, we had to speak to
activists, locals,
some fighters who are fighting
against Islamic

14:02.942 --> 14:05.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
State, and people who are trying
to document
human rights abuses.

14:05.211 --> 14:10.116 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Do mass graves also
-- always
mean mass killings?

14:10.149 --> 14:14.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That is to say, did all of the
people -- or
the bodies that you found in
these graves

14:14.420 --> 14:17.690 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
all come from single episodes,
single assaults?

14:17.724 --> 14:21.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LORI HINNANT: Not necessarily,
although, largely,
they did.

14:21.794 --> 14:24.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And even for some of them, it's
not clear
who is even in them.

14:24.897 --> 14:28.301 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The graves have not been
excavated and they
are untouched.

14:28.334 --> 14:31.270 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Others are in territory that no
one has seen.

14:31.304 --> 14:36.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The pit outside Mosul and
another one in Syria,
for example, we know from
Islamic State's

14:37.009 --> 14:41.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
own propaganda that they have
buried hundreds,
if not more, bodies in them.

14:41.080 --> 14:44.617 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they just tossed them in
really without
a thought.

14:44.650 --> 14:48.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have no idea why the people
were killed
exactly or when.

14:48.654 --> 14:51.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in those cases, yes, the
victims are killed
at different times.

14:52.024 --> 14:54.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Sinjar, they were all killed
at the same
time.

14:54.260 --> 14:56.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Do we know how they
were killed?

14:56.496 --> 14:57.630 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Are we talking about gunshots?

14:57.663 --> 15:00.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Are we talking about sometimes
in some cases
illness?

15:00.133 --> 15:02.168 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LORI HINNANT: Illness seems
unlikely.

15:02.201 --> 15:04.070 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's mostly gunshots.

15:04.103 --> 15:08.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The assault on Sinjar, for
example, it was
some gunshots.

15:08.374 --> 15:09.342 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Some people were beheaded.

15:09.375 --> 15:11.577 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
A few were run over by cars.

15:11.611 --> 15:18.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the site that holds the
bodies of about
1,700 Iraqi soldiers, they were
all gunned

15:18.217 --> 15:21.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down after being forced to lie
down on the
ground.

15:21.254 --> 15:25.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Same with the Shiite prisoners
of the prison
in Mosul.

15:25.725 --> 15:29.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You said that, in
Syria, it was
difficult to physically get to
the actual

15:29.862 --> 15:31.497 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
grave sites.

15:31.531 --> 15:33.332 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then how were you able to
document what happened?

15:33.366 --> 15:36.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LORI HINNANT: Well, what we did
was, we relied
on multiple sources.

15:36.836 --> 15:41.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we didn't just wait for one
person to
say, we think there is a mass
grave here.

15:41.774 --> 15:45.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We tried to find a variety of
sources, including
locals.

15:45.444 --> 15:50.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some people sent us photos,
which we could
help by geolocating and by
coordinating with

15:50.850 --> 15:52.785 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
what Islamic State's own
propaganda says.

15:52.819 --> 15:55.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have made no effort to hide
what they're
doing.

15:55.054 --> 15:59.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Can the bodies that
are then retrieved,
or are they being retrieved, can
they be identified?

15:59.992 --> 16:03.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LORI HINNANT: Well, that's the
complicated
part right now, that they
largely aren't being

16:03.930 --> 16:10.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
retrieved, for a variety of
reasons, a want
of money, want of political
will, and very,

16:10.169 --> 16:11.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
very unstable areas.

16:12.004 --> 16:16.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Sinjar Mountain, although it's
been largely
taken back from Islamic State,
still remains

16:16.108 --> 16:19.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a part of it inside a no-man's
land within
reach of mortars.

16:19.912 --> 16:25.384 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some of the sites are believed
to be booby-trapped
and are too unsafe to go in to.

16:25.418 --> 16:28.654 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The bodies in some cases have
been identified.

16:28.688 --> 16:30.857 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Relatives can find personal
belongings.

16:30.890 --> 16:33.459 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They can sometimes even find
I.D.s.

16:33.492 --> 16:38.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there is a center in the
city of Dohuk
where they are keeping some of
these belongings,

16:38.531 --> 16:42.668 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in hope of finding other
survivors who might
be able to say who they were.

16:42.702 --> 16:48.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Has anyone ever been
charged or
jailed or in any way punished
for these deaths?

16:48.374 --> 16:53.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LORI HINNANT: There has been
justice done
in one case, quite recently
actually, in the

16:53.346 --> 16:58.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
death at Camp Speicher of the
1,700 Iraqi
soldiers.

16:58.150 --> 17:03.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just on August 21, 36 men were
hanged who
had been convicted in those
killings.

17:03.389 --> 17:07.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As part of this
investigation,
Lori, and you talked to people
who were survivors

17:07.693 --> 17:09.462 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or witnesses.

17:09.495 --> 17:12.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Were you able to talk to any of
the relatives
of people who think that their
loved ones

17:12.265 --> 17:13.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
might be in one of these graves?

17:13.499 --> 17:15.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LORI HINNANT: We did.

17:15.268 --> 17:20.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At one point, we went to an area
just outside
the town of Hardan, Iraq, and we
met a man

17:20.539 --> 17:24.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there who originally was just
there to tell
us about the graves.

17:24.644 --> 17:29.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was one of the leaders of the
village,
and he wanted to tell us about
the graves

17:29.682 --> 17:33.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and how much they wished that
they would be
excavated and that the people
who were buried

17:33.219 --> 17:35.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in there would get a proper
burial.

17:35.121 --> 17:40.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it took some time before he
finally acknowledged
that, in fact, two of his adult
sons were

17:40.226 --> 17:42.128 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
among the victims of that
killing.

17:42.161 --> 17:46.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And after a little while, he and
I talked
for a bit longer, and he invited
another young

17:46.732 --> 17:51.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
man down from the hillside town
just above
where the killings had taken
place, and said

17:51.671 --> 17:54.006 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he actually saw the killings.

17:54.040 --> 17:58.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Turned out that the young man
whose name was
Arkon (ph) had never spoken with
the father

17:58.811 --> 18:01.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about what happened the day his
two sons were
-- died.

18:01.747 --> 18:03.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was really chilling.

18:03.616 --> 18:09.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As we were standing there, the
two men discussed
the events of this horrific day
that they

18:09.588 --> 18:13.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
feel as though they're reliving
every single
day that they pass the grave.

18:13.592 --> 18:17.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Will this father
ever be able
to retrieve the bodies of his
sons?

18:17.163 --> 18:18.631 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LORI HINNANT: He hopes to.

18:18.664 --> 18:20.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He sounded very resigned to it.

18:20.800 --> 18:26.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He said he wanted the
international community
to understand that they couldn't
keep reliving

18:26.772 --> 18:28.574 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the sorrow all of the time.

18:28.607 --> 18:32.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All he wanted was a proper place
for his sons
to be laid to rest.

18:32.979 --> 18:36.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Lori Hinnant of the
Associated
Press, thank you very much.

18:36.215 --> 18:41.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LORI HINNANT: Thank you.

18:41.420 --> 18:51.097 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

