question.

20:39.972 --> 20:41.340 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Like, I was going to college.

20:41.373 --> 20:43.175 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That was that.

20:43.209 --> 20:46.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that's kind of why I
want to teach
in Chicago Public Schools, is
because they

20:46.479 --> 20:50.916 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
don't have the same
opportunities that I did
growing up in the suburbs.

20:50.950 --> 20:54.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it's just going to be a new
experience.

20:54.553 --> 20:59.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: This morning, Morgan
is leaving
for this unique teaching
fellowship that takes

20:59.458 --> 21:06.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
her out of Rolling Meadows for a
new home
in Auburn Gresham, a
predominantly African-American

21:06.432 --> 21:12.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
community on Chicago's South
Side, one of
four neighborhoods fellows are
placed in for

21:12.538 --> 21:23.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one month, all with high-poverty
schools,
many with high crime rates as
well.

21:23.282 --> 21:30.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a nonstop four weeks,
assisting in the
classroom in the morning,
volunteering in

21:30.656 --> 21:32.825 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the afternoon.

21:32.858 --> 21:43.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Classes and seminars fill
evenings and weekends,
all to help them appreciate and
understand

21:43.202 --> 21:45.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the culture of these
communities.

21:45.471 --> 21:49.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT LEE, STEP-UP, Illinois
State University:
And they hope that, when this is
all finished,

21:49.208 --> 21:52.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that you come back and become a
teacher for
their community.

21:52.344 --> 21:55.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Robert Lee runs this
fellowship,
called STEP-UP.

21:55.514 --> 22:02.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT LEE: This infusion, this
allowing candidates
to experience firsthand and
start to confront

22:02.087 --> 22:07.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their -- their own race, their
own class,
their own sources of privilege,
leads to a

22:07.927 --> 22:10.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
much stronger teacher when they
enter the
field.

22:10.563 --> 22:17.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Only 7 years old,
with 144 participants
so far, it's a small program,
but one that

22:17.803 --> 22:22.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
takes enormous effort, including
finding funding,
about $8,000 a fellow.

22:22.675 --> 22:25.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT LEE: That's where the
challenge is
going to be.

22:25.678 --> 22:30.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Virtually every
teacher college
requires so-called cultural
competency training,

22:30.783 --> 22:35.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but Professor Carol Lee says
many programs
come up short.

22:35.221 --> 22:39.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CAROL LEE, Northeastern
University: The notion
of cultural competence is often
pitched as

22:39.792 --> 22:45.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something special you need to
know if you're
working with colored kids.

22:45.731 --> 22:48.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I'm saying, I don't care
where you're
teaching.

22:48.901 --> 22:56.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The cultural competence means
that I have
to go into that community with
the humility

22:56.175 --> 22:57.910 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in order to learn.

22:57.943 --> 23:04.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: One of the key ways
that STEP-UP
fellows learn is from the host
families.

23:04.550 --> 23:12.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yolanda Smith will provide
Morgan meals and
a place to sleep, but, most
importantly, lessons

23:12.558 --> 23:16.795 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that can't be taught in the
classroom.

23:16.829 --> 23:19.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you hope Morgan leaves
this neighborhood
with?

23:19.131 --> 23:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YOLANDA SMITH, Host Mom: Just to
learn about
us, and don't believe the hype.

23:23.202 --> 23:25.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: What is the hype, in
your view?

23:25.237 --> 23:28.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
YOLANDA SMITH: That we're
shiftless and violent.

23:28.807 --> 23:34.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I just want us -- want her
to see the
human side of us, not what is
portrayed on

23:34.480 --> 23:35.948 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the media.

23:35.981 --> 23:38.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: We're so thankful that
you're watching
over her while she's here.

23:38.817 --> 23:40.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
YOLANDA SMITH: I sure do, me and
God.

23:40.286 --> 23:41.253 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: Yes.

23:41.287 --> 23:42.454 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

23:42.488 --> 23:44.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Not all of the
fellows are from
the suburbs.

23:44.990 --> 23:46.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Asia-Ana Williams grew up in
Chicago.

23:46.692 --> 23:50.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ASIA-ANA WILLIAMS, Student,
Illinois State
University: I'm, like, a little
nervous.

23:50.362 --> 23:56.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is going to be my first
time teaching,
so I don't know how I will do.

23:56.068 --> 23:57.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's, like, scary to think
about.

23:58.003 --> 24:02.141 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: Asia-ana was
recruited by Illinois
State while in high school as
part of an effort

24:02.174 --> 24:05.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to encourage students of color
to become teachers.

24:05.077 --> 24:09.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ASIA-ANA WILLIAMS: I want to
come home to
students who look just like me,
who have been

24:10.015 --> 24:14.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
through things just like I have,
and help
them the way my teachers helped
me.

24:14.186 --> 24:24.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: She too is in an
unfamiliar neighborhood,
the largely Hispanic community
of Little Village.

24:24.263 --> 24:28.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It didn't take her long to feel
at home.

24:28.767 --> 24:31.236 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: This is really good, so try
it.

24:31.270 --> 24:34.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAMS: My host family can't
get rid of
me now.

24:34.039 --> 24:35.808 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Like, I love them too much.

24:35.841 --> 24:37.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Yes, they're pretty much stuck
with me.

24:37.710 --> 24:43.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: The Velazco family
has taken in
fellows since the STEP-UP
program began seven

24:43.415 --> 24:44.750 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
years ago.

24:44.783 --> 24:47.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you tell these student
teachers who
come to your house?

24:47.486 --> 24:49.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TONY VELAZCO, Host Dad: Not to
have the savior
mentality.

24:49.555 --> 24:52.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're not coming in here to
save people.

24:52.591 --> 24:55.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're here to be part of the
community.

24:55.728 --> 24:58.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they really have to get to
know where
the kids are coming from in
order to be able

24:59.031 --> 25:02.968 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to teach them better, to reach
them, to inspire
them.

25:03.001 --> 25:10.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: Finding host
families and local
schools is done with the support
of community

25:10.409 --> 25:15.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
groups, such as the one run by
Carlos Nelson
in Auburn Gresham.

25:15.180 --> 25:18.550 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CARLOS NELSON, Greater
Auburn-Gresham Development
Corporation: The teachers in our
schools have

25:18.584 --> 25:20.085 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
daunting tasks.

25:20.119 --> 25:24.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's way beyond just being
able to teach
kids math and reading.

25:24.623 --> 25:29.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they're also having to deal
with social,
emotional challenges, kids that
haven't had

25:29.361 --> 25:32.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a full night's sleep, that
haven't had a full
meal.

25:32.431 --> 25:38.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's why we need to
prepare educators
to be more in tune with teaching
the kids

25:38.937 --> 25:44.410 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in our South Side community.

25:44.443 --> 25:56.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: The hope with a
program like this
one is that, if teachers are
truly trained

25:56.989 --> 26:03.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to teach in urban schools, not
only will they
take jobs here, but they will
stay.

26:03.362 --> 26:05.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
VANESSA PUENTES HERNANDEZ,
Assistant Principal,
Farragut Career Academy: Hey,
guys, what's

26:05.097 --> 26:06.799 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up?

26:06.832 --> 26:08.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Assistant Principal
Vanessa Puentes
Hernandez, who has worked in the
district

26:08.400 --> 26:12.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for a decade, has seen teachers
come and go.

26:12.104 --> 26:17.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Turnover in some Chicago schools
is as high
as 50 percent over four years.

26:17.509 --> 26:18.677 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
VANESSA PUENTES HERNANDEZ: It
takes a village.

26:18.710 --> 26:20.746 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It really does.

26:20.779 --> 26:25.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it's important to learn
about the community
that you work in, because you
want to be invested

26:25.451 --> 26:30.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in that, not as an outsider
coming in and
maybe gaining some experience
and leaving,

26:30.422 --> 26:32.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but as someone who truly wants
to create change.

26:32.758 --> 26:34.993 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WOMAN: That's a lot of work.

26:35.027 --> 26:35.994 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's a sacrifice.

26:36.028 --> 26:37.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: It really is.

26:37.429 --> 26:39.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VANESSA PUENTES HERNANDEZ: They
care so much
about their community.

26:39.331 --> 26:45.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's kind of sad to see like how
much effort
they're kind of putting in, and
they still

26:45.504 --> 26:48.740 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
get seen in such negative
lighting.

26:48.774 --> 26:57.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Most of STEP-UP's
graduates end
up in Chicago or other high-need
schools.

26:57.749 --> 27:02.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And over 80 percent are still in
the classroom
after five years.

27:02.588 --> 27:08.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ASIA-ANA WILLIAMS: We all came
from so many
different backgrounds, but I
think that the

27:08.160 --> 27:12.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
common ground was always that we
all wanted
to be good teachers.

27:12.731 --> 27:17.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These schools deserve good
teachers, just
like any other school district.

27:17.336 --> 27:19.171 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: And you want to be
one of them?

27:19.204 --> 27:20.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ASIA-ANA WILLIAMS: And I want to
be one of
them.

27:20.472 --> 27:22.307 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I am going to be one of
them.

27:22.341 --> 27:32.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: And with the help of
this program,
she's likely to have some
company.

27:32.184 --> 27:37.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Reporting from Chicago, I'm Lisa
Stark of
Education Week for the "PBS
NewsHour."

27:37.723 --> 27:47.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Turning now to
politics:
How much have team Clinton and
team Trump

27:47.766 --> 27:54.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Turning now to
politics:
How much have team Clinton and
team Trump

27:54.907 --> 27:59.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
invested in their on-the-ground
outreach,
their ground games, if you will,
to get their

27:59.978 --> 28:02.581 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
supporters out to the polls this
fall?

28:02.614 --> 28:05.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Correspondent Lisa Desjardins
and digital
politics editor Daniel Bush
tackle that in

28:05.784 --> 28:08.287 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their new piece out today on our
"NewsHour"
Web site.

28:08.320 --> 28:09.955 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And Lisa joins me now.

28:09.988 --> 28:14.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you went out to different
campaign facilities,
offices out in these key states.

28:14.660 --> 28:15.961 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right.

28:15.994 --> 28:17.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What's the
difference when
you go into them?

28:17.829 --> 28:20.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: This is an
important difference,
because now we're in the crucial
last two

28:20.465 --> 28:22.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
months of this campaign.

28:22.234 --> 28:24.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The map, I think, tells the
story the best.

28:24.136 --> 28:25.904 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And this wasn't easy to
pinpoint.

28:25.938 --> 28:28.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But let's look at the Trump
campaign offices.

28:28.206 --> 28:33.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He right now has 88 offices in
key battleground
states, the states that pretty
much will decide

28:33.412 --> 28:34.513 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this election.

28:34.546 --> 28:35.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Look at those circles.

28:35.681 --> 28:37.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They indicate how many offices
are in that
state.

28:37.449 --> 28:39.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, the bigger
the circle,
the more offices, yes?

28:39.084 --> 28:40.018 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Exactly.

28:40.052 --> 28:41.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: OK.

28:41.186 --> 28:42.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Now let's look
at the Clinton
map.

28:42.054 --> 28:43.889 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You see a very stark difference
there.

28:43.922 --> 28:49.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinton has more than three
times as many
offices as Donald Trump right
now going into

28:49.227 --> 28:52.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Labor Day, the traditional start
of the presidential
campaign season.

28:52.898 --> 28:56.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, one thing I have to note,
the Donald
Trump campaign says more coming.

28:56.201 --> 29:00.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They say about over 100 are
going to come
online in the next week, but
they're not open

29:00.105 --> 29:01.340 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

29:01.373 --> 29:03.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is especially a problem
for them
in some key states.

29:03.875 --> 29:09.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's look at four key states
where we know
things could be decisive,
Florida, North Carolina,

29:09.314 --> 29:11.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Ohio, Pennsylvania.

29:11.049 --> 29:15.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right now, Donald Trump has just
20 offices
in those four mega-states,
Hillary Clinton

29:15.554 --> 29:16.655 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
136.

29:16.688 --> 29:20.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Hari, Florida, we know, has been
decisive
in the past.

29:20.192 --> 29:21.460 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a great example here.

29:21.493 --> 29:23.895 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Donald Trump right now just has
one office
open there.

29:23.929 --> 29:28.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, one of the
questions
would be, well, how important
are those offices?

29:28.166 --> 29:31.737 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What's the work that happens at
those offices?

29:31.770 --> 29:34.239 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And does it matter in this
election?

29:34.272 --> 29:35.240 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right.

29:35.273 --> 29:36.241 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why should we care about the
ground game?

29:36.274 --> 29:38.076 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It seems like inside politics.

29:38.110 --> 29:43.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The ground game has decided at
least the last
two elections, maybe going back
farther to

29:43.915 --> 29:45.651 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
even George W. Bush as well.

29:45.684 --> 29:47.185 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Traditionally, it is critical.

29:47.219 --> 29:51.790 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are the places where
volunteers identify
and actually sway voters.

29:51.823 --> 29:54.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Phone banks happen there,
canvassing operations.

29:54.559 --> 29:58.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is kind of the breathing
heart of usual
campaigns.

29:58.063 --> 29:59.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, it doesn't matter this
year.

29:59.765 --> 30:04.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Trump campaign says, no,
that they have
an operation that defies
convention, that

30:04.236 --> 30:07.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they like that, they don't need
as many on-the-ground
offices.

30:07.906 --> 30:13.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They say, instead, their
groundswell of support
is a different type of campaign,
and they

30:13.445 --> 30:18.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think that this traditional type
of tactic
is something they don't need as
much as other

30:18.316 --> 30:19.685 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
campaigns.

30:19.718 --> 30:20.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And they're
also saying
they're going mobile.

30:20.886 --> 30:22.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have got some R.V.s,
instead of fixed
locations.

